{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"39d7f941-a0e3-4c05-a8da-acb3d30f9e84","content":"In .NET MAUI, `Application` no longer has `OnStart`/`OnSleep`/`OnResume`. Instead, use **`Window` lifecycle events** by overriding `CreateWindow` in your `App` class:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnStart */ };\n    window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnSleep */ };\n    window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnResume */ };\n    window.Destroying += (s, e) => { /* cleanup on close */ };\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Mapping summary:**\n\n| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI (Window event) |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `Window.Created` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `Window.Stopped` |\n| `OnResume()` | `Window.Resumed` |\n\nFor **platform-specific** lifecycle hooks (e.g., Android `OnActivityResult`), use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android.OnStop(activity => { /* ... */ }));\n#elif IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios.WillTerminate(app => { /* ... */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"cd4d72d9-4bdc-4f72-8384-8b943a16df4f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly without needing to search the codebase.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` on the `Application` class.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the lifecycle model changed. Instead of those overrides, you use the `Window` lifecycle events or the cross-platform lifecycle events via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`, or you can override `CreateWindow` and hook into `Window` events.\n \nSo while `Application` still technically has those same virtual methods in MAUI, the recommended approach is to use the `Window` lifecycle events like `Created`, `Activated`, `Deactivated`, `Stopped`, `Resumed`, and `Destroying` instead, or leverage platform-specific lifecycle configuration through `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`. Window lifecycle event handlers...","outputTokens":904,"requestId":"77C2:176D78:7F1CE22:8D51E9C:69EABEC3"},"id":"7caa0850-077a-4c52-a38b-446267eb0c99","timestamp":"2026-04-24T00:52:35.346Z","parentId":"37960813-bc87-4a79-aedb-2b354f6dc2c6"}
